The belief ‚ or disbelief in the propositions propounded was not regarded as likely to affect a man's lot either in this world or the next. The tendency of speculation, therefore, both among the later Greeks and the Romans, was towards a philosophy of life, character, and conduct, and this tendency amongst the Romans was specially assisted by the legal and practical directiou of their minds. The favourite topics of discussion were not the nature of the Gods or our relations to them, much less our duties towards them, but our relations and duties to each other, the main objects of life, wherein consists the perfectiori of human nature, by what means we can attain that perfectiori, and other questions of asimilar character. lt was the answer to these questions, we might say, and not the answer to theological enquiries, which furnisbed the spiritual sustenance of the Greeks and Romans.
